[[File:Lord Justice Rigby.jpg|thumb|right|<center>"Mr Solicitor"<br />As caricatured in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine 1868-1914)|Vanity Fair]], 31 August 1893</center>]]
[[File:John Rigby Vanity Fair 1901-03-28.jpeg|thumb|right|<center>"a blunt Lord Justice"<br>As caricatured by Spy ([[Leslie Ward]]) in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine)|Vanity Fair]], March 1901</center>]]
'''Sir John Rigby''', [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] (8 January 1834 &ndash; 26 July 1903), was a [[United Kingdom|British]] judge and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician who sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] between 1885 and 1894.

==Background and education==
Rigby was born in Runcorn, Cheshire, the son of Thomas Rigby of [[Halton, Cheshire]], and his wife Elizabeth Kendal.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/debrettshouseo1886londuoft Debretts Guide to the House of Commons 1886]</ref>  He attended [[Liverpool College]] before going to [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] in 1853. He graduated as [[Second Wrangler]] in 1856, also being placed second for the [[Smith's Prize]]. He became a fellow of Trinity in 1856 and was [[Call to the Bar|called to the Bar]] at [[Lincoln's Inn]] in 1860.<ref name="Venn">{{acad|id=RGBY852J|name=Rigby, John}}</ref><ref name=obit>{{cite news |title=Death of Sir John Rigby |work=[[The Times]] |page=6 |date=27 July 1903 }}</ref>

==Legal career==
The story of how Rigby came to the Bar may be found on pg. 120 of the 1958 memoir “B-berry and I Look Back”, by [[Dornford Yates]].
In 1875 Rigby was appointed junior counsel to the [[Her Majesty's Treasury|Treasury]].<ref name=obit/> In 1881 he "took silk", becoming a [[Queen's Counsel]].<ref name=obit/> He distinguished himself as an advocate, and was frequently involved in bringing appeals to the judicial committee of the [[House of Lords]].<ref name=obit/> Rigby was twice briefly a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] [[Member of Parliament]]. He was elected as MP for the [[Wisbech (UK Parliament constituency)|Wisbech division of Cambridgeshire]] at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1885|1885 general election]], but lost the seat when another [[United Kingdom general election, 1886|election was held in 1886]].<ref>{{hansard-contribs | mr-john-rigby | Sir John Rigby }}</ref>

In [[United Kingdom general election, 1892|1892]] Rigby returned to parliament, when he was among a number of Liberals who gained seats from the government parties in [[Scotland]]. He was elected at [[Forfar (UK Parliament constituency)|Forfarshire]], unseating the [[Liberal Unionist]], [[James William Barclay|James Barclay]].<ref name=obit/> He was appointed [[Solicitor General for England and Wales]] in [[Fourth Gladstone Ministry|William Gladstone's new government]], and received a [[knight bachelor|knighthood]] on 26 November 1892.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=26351 |date=6 December 1892 |page=7153 }}</ref> On 3 May 1894 Rigby became [[Attorney General for England and Wales]].<ref name=obit/>

On 19 October 1894 he vacated his Commons seat when he was appointed a [[Lord Justice of Appeal]], in succession to Sir [[Horace Davey]]. He was sworn of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] at the same time.<ref name=Venn/><ref name=obit/><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=26563 |date=23 October 1894 |page=5928 }}</ref> He served on the Court of Appeal until his retirement in 1901,<ref name=obit/> when he was granted an annuity of £3,500.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27372 |date=5 November 1901 |page=7144}}</ref>

===Judgments===
*''[[The Satanita]]'' [1897] AC 59 - Contract law case atypical of the conventional offer & acceptance pattern seen in English law. Rigby's decision at appeal affirmed by the [[Judicial functions of the House of Lords#Appeal|House of Lords]].

==Personal life==
A few years before his retirement, Rigby had suffered a severe fall, and never fully recovered his health. He died aged 69, unmarried, at his home at [[Chelsea Embankment]], London in July 1903.<ref name=obit/>

